    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "ok i get it, counter-clockwise. so if i'm at eb major, i go counter-clockwise to find its relative minor. but why is it called a \"circle\" anyway? it's just a bunch of notes and intervals, why does it have to be a repeating loop or a cycle?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Circle of Fifths is called a circle because it represents a fundamental, repeating pattern in Western harmony and tonality. It's not just a random collection of notes; it's the very structure of how keys relate to each other through the perfect fifth interval. Every key is connected to every other key through a series of these fifths, making it a closed loop.\n\nThis looping structure is essential because it shows that music isn't just isolated pieces; it's interconnected. It's like a network of key relationships, and the cycle ensures that you can always find a path from any key to any other key using only fifths.",
      "source": "target",
